rotations can show players that you're willing to work with them instead of against them.

241
00:12:05,673 --> 00:12:08,798
By listening to the feedback and suggestions of your community, you show them that their

242
00:12:08,838 --> 00:12:13,365
opinions are valued. It's not just about listening, though. You have to act on it. And

243
00:12:13,405 --> 00:12:16,469
don't make false promises telling them that you're going to do something that you're unsure

244
00:12:16,549 --> 00:12:19,874
of, but promise them that you can look into it and make sure that you report back.

245
00:12:21,343 --> 00:12:25,024
Sometimes getting these changes up and running quickly can be difficult, but keeping communication

246
00:12:25,064 --> 00:12:26,964
channels open with players helps considerably.

247
00:12:27,724 --> 00:12:31,345
Through community suggestions, we've run numerous tournaments and events in our games outside

248
00:12:31,365 --> 00:12:35,406
of regulated times and have seen a three or four times increase in sales and a lot of

249
00:12:35,466 --> 00:12:37,127
positive sentiment for such a small change.

250
00:12:38,967 --> 00:12:43,068
As a case study, let's take the Centaurians event that we held in one of our games, Age

251
00:12:43,088 --> 00:12:45,369
of Legends, our fantasy-themed war game.

252
00:12:46,905 --> 00:12:50,967
In addition to battling, competing in clans, and completing missions, crafting has always

253
00:12:50,987 --> 00:12:52,588
been an important mechanic within our games.

254
00:12:53,108 --> 00:12:56,350
Players liked upgrading their items to make them even more powerful, but were limited

255
00:12:56,390 --> 00:12:57,851
by the number of items they could carry.

256
00:12:58,271 --> 00:13:02,033
So this presented a unique opportunity to give players exactly what they wanted, stronger

257
00:13:02,093 --> 00:13:05,555
items they could use in battle, along with a more interactive event that had been requested

258
00:13:05,595 --> 00:13:05,975
for months.

259
00:13:08,944 --> 00:13:13,866
The premise was a bit complicated, but ultimately it allowed players to focus on acquiring items

260
00:13:13,886 --> 00:13:15,466
that they could craft into a stronger item.

261
00:13:16,286 --> 00:13:19,527
This image was shared on our Facebook and Twitter pages, not only to give players a

262
00:13:19,567 --> 00:13:23,088
better visual opportunity to understand what needed to be done, but also to grow those

263
00:13:23,108 --> 00:13:23,609
pages out.

264
00:13:25,449 --> 00:13:28,150
And again, we were met with resistance from the community.

265
00:13:28,730 --> 00:13:31,731
Although they had been asking for something like this numerous times, there was a fear

266
00:13:31,771 --> 00:13:34,532
that they would miss out on obtaining these limited items.

267
00:13:35,590 --> 00:13:38,893
players with low level accounts were frustrated that they may not get the high level items

268
00:13:39,173 --> 00:13:43,177
without having to pay for it. And as soon as the event started, many called for boycotts

269
00:13:43,478 --> 00:13:47,802
and others called us useless and insulted our developers before even trying out the event.

270
00:13:49,724 --> 00:13:53,007
But following these complaints, we still had plenty of positive comments in the forums as

271
00:13:53,048 --> 00:13:55,570
well. People giving us credit for trying something new.

272
00:13:56,819 --> 00:13:58,840
One of our players congratulated us for doing something

273
00:13:58,900 --> 00:14:01,843
different, saying that they would still get great items

274
00:14:01,903 --> 00:14:06,327
just for participating, and that some events are just

275
00:14:06,367 --> 00:14:07,588
intended to be difficult.

276
00:14:08,749 --> 00:14:12,132
And thankfully, this player said that with the release of

277
00:14:12,172 --> 00:14:14,374
the event, we managed to make the game interesting again.

278
00:14:16,218 --> 00:14:18,520
Finally, a post by a player who goes out of their way

279
00:14:18,661 --> 00:14:20,602
to help the community better understand the benefits

280
00:14:20,642 --> 00:14:21,763
of participating in the event,

281
00:14:22,224 --> 00:14:23,845
even if they aren't entirely happy with it.

282
00:14:24,566 --> 00:14:26,267
He addressed the concerns of the low-level players

283
00:14:26,427 --> 00:14:28,749
and even gave them some stretch goals to shoot for

284
00:14:29,290 --> 00:14:30,791
to benefit themselves from the tournament.

285
00:14:31,392 --> 00:14:33,133
This post alone encouraged the vast majority

286
00:14:33,153 --> 00:14:35,115
of the community to actually try out the tournament

287
00:14:35,375 --> 00:14:36,736
and increase the amount of positive sentiment

288
00:14:36,756 --> 00:14:37,537
for trying something new.

289
00:14:40,477 --> 00:14:44,520
Explaining the worth of something like this is very difficult. And on the surface, knowing

290
00:14:44,540 --> 00:14:47,822
that players simply participated isn't quite enough to justify the amount of work that went

291
00:14:47,862 --> 00:14:52,944
into it. In a worst case scenario, we would have created a tournament that had flooded our

292
00:14:53,005 --> 00:14:57,487
economy with really strong weapons and it could have caused a collapse in our game's balance.

293
00:14:58,127 --> 00:15:01,569
Which brings up a more measurable question. What did our metrics look like?

294
00:15:02,840 --> 00:15:04,681
So we had a few thousand players participate in the

295
00:15:04,701 --> 00:15:06,701
weekend event.

296
00:15:06,741 --> 00:15:07,562
80% reached the first tier.

297
00:15:07,662 --> 00:15:09,683
So right away, if you just played along and you hit the

298
00:15:09,723 --> 00:15:11,644
first tier, you'd get some free premium currency.

299
00:15:14,225 --> 00:15:15,845
65% of participants received free items.

300
00:15:16,246 --> 00:15:18,707
And those were worth much more than the free premium currency

301
00:15:18,727 --> 00:15:19,307
that we gave them.

302
00:15:20,387 --> 00:15:23,209
And only 1% actually obtained and managed to assemble the

303
00:15:23,289 --> 00:15:25,710
ultimate item, which isn't necessarily a bad thing.

304
00:15:25,950 --> 00:15:28,291
It promotes the limited nature of the item and the prestige

305
00:15:28,311 --> 00:15:29,691
of actually being able to obtain one.

306
00:15:30,964 --> 00:15:34,268
And our metrics showed the company that investing in new ideas like this is actually a good

307
00:15:34,309 --> 00:15:34,509
thing.

308
00:15:35,150 --> 00:15:36,992
Month over month, our revenue in the game grew by 47%.

309
00:15:38,434 --> 00:15:41,818
And even had a tail that extended into April, which was usually one of our slower months

310
00:15:41,858 --> 00:15:42,139
in the year.

311
00:15:45,058 --> 00:15:48,359
Next is admitting when you're wrong or admitting when something isn't working correctly.

312
00:15:49,120 --> 00:15:51,260
And it's imperative in combating negativity.

313
00:15:51,961 --> 00:15:54,242
It's also a trait that all community managers need to embrace.

314
00:15:55,042 --> 00:15:59,264
There's a need to protect your integrity or stand strong against accusations, but telling

315
00:15:59,304 --> 00:16:01,205
players when you know something sucks can help a lot.

316
00:16:02,672 --> 00:16:07,254
In our game Crime Inc., we have items called underbosses. They can be purchased using

317
00:16:07,314 --> 00:16:12,217
premium or soft currency and give stat boosts to player accounts. They have great art and

318
00:16:12,257 --> 00:16:18,460
allow players to collect a council of criminals to help attack others. Following a lengthy

319
00:16:18,480 --> 00:16:22,762
investigation, we had found that one of our premium underbosses, so ones that you actually

320
00:16:22,782 --> 00:16:27,724
had to spend real money to obtain, uh, needed to be rebalanced. And the item was initially

321
00:16:27,784 --> 00:16:30,605
designed without a long term plan in mind. We had

322
00:16:31,768 --> 00:16:33,168
we had to make a really difficult decision.

323
00:16:33,288 --> 00:16:35,569
We had to reduce the benefit that the item was giving,

324
00:16:35,869 --> 00:16:37,309
even though players had spent real money on it.

325
00:16:39,470 --> 00:16:40,570
Her name was Meryl Newsome.

326
00:16:41,631 --> 00:16:43,051
And with the right items equipped,

327
00:16:43,271 --> 00:16:45,512
Meryl could provide players with nearly unlimited

328
00:16:45,592 --> 00:16:47,232
recharges to their health and stats.

329
00:16:47,672 --> 00:16:49,853
So it effectively let players play for free

330
00:16:50,033 --> 00:16:50,993
for as long as they wanted.

331
00:16:51,474 --> 00:16:52,994
And for a free-to-play title like Crime Inc.,

332
00:16:53,414 --> 00:16:54,815
this was very, very dangerous.

333
00:16:56,082 --> 00:17:00,064
And obviously this blew up in the forums with players calling us greedy bastards, saying

334
00:17:00,084 --> 00:17:03,886
that we're bending the laws, committing fraud and saying that the decision to make the change

335
00:17:03,926 --> 00:17:08,929
was highway robbery. Players were urging others to contact third party services for full

336
00:17:08,989 --> 00:17:12,451
payment refunds, resetting their accounts and many were contacting us with some of the

337
00:17:12,471 --> 00:17:16,193
more belligerent and abusive behavior that we've encountered in the company. And this

338
00:17:16,233 --> 00:17:21,276
comment isn't even the tip of the iceberg. So how do you deal with something like this

339
00:17:21,356 --> 00:17:22,517
without popping a vein in your head?

340
00:17:23,709 --> 00:17:25,971
In our experience, admitting exactly what happened

341
00:17:26,091 --> 00:17:28,112
and why it had to happen means that you have to admit

342
00:17:28,172 --> 00:17:30,034
that the initial design was ill-informed

343
00:17:30,374 --> 00:17:32,055
and that the fault lies in the hands of the company

344
00:17:32,375 --> 00:17:33,736
and relieves the players of blame.

345
00:17:35,337 --> 00:17:36,798
Although players are drastically affected

346
00:17:36,838 --> 00:17:38,039
in rebalancing cases like this,

347
00:17:38,480 --> 00:17:40,241
finding loopholes is understandable.

348
00:17:40,701 --> 00:17:42,583
In order to keep the game fair and balanced for all players,

349
00:17:42,883 --> 00:17:45,084
it's important for the community to not only understand

350
00:17:45,144 --> 00:17:46,205
why the decision was made,

351
00:17:46,545 --> 00:17:48,667
but then to give them a platform to voice their concerns.

352
00:17:49,775 --> 00:17:52,276
We spent an exhausting afternoon in the forums,

353
00:17:52,336 --> 00:17:54,397
responding directly to player concerns and feedback.

354
00:17:54,957 --> 00:17:56,058
No question was off the table.

355
00:17:57,119 --> 00:17:59,520
We spent a considerable amount of time doing our best

356
00:17:59,560 --> 00:18:01,041
to quell the concerns of our community,

357
00:18:01,461 --> 00:18:02,722
and honestly, it helped.

358
00:18:03,962 --> 00:18:05,543
We had numerous players praising us

359
00:18:05,583 --> 00:18:06,824
for taking the time to talk to them

360
00:18:07,084 --> 00:18:09,325
and for trying to find a compromise for their concerns.

361
00:18:10,006 --> 00:18:12,267
Sure, there were still plenty of upset users,

362
00:18:12,827 --> 00:18:14,768
but knowing that we took the time to address the concerns

363
00:18:14,968 --> 00:18:16,109
took a lot of the pressure off.

364
00:18:17,233 --> 00:18:19,454
In summary, we found that players are substantially

365
00:18:19,534 --> 00:18:22,135
less likely to directly attack you if you put up your hands

366
00:18:22,375 --> 00:18:23,436
and you say, my bad.

367
00:18:24,136 --> 00:18:25,236
And that goes for bugs too.

368
00:18:25,677 --> 00:18:26,797
Tell players what's going on.

369
00:18:26,897 --> 00:18:27,877
Are you working on a fix?

370
00:18:28,117 --> 00:18:29,198
What's the status of the fix?

371
00:18:29,658 --> 00:18:30,918
It shows players that you're trying to manage

372
00:18:30,938 --> 00:18:32,439
their expectations the best that you can.

373
00:18:34,820 --> 00:18:37,401
And my final point, it's important to not come at players

374
00:18:37,461 --> 00:18:38,201
from on high.

375
00:18:38,861 --> 00:18:40,042
Representing your company is critical,

376
00:18:40,082 --> 00:18:42,403
but also being able to talk to your players on their level

377
00:18:42,443 --> 00:18:44,183
is necessary in improving communication.

378
00:18:45,817 --> 00:18:49,380
Saying that you understand your player's frustration isn't always helpful.

379
00:18:49,740 --> 00:18:53,223
It can come across as dismissive if you don't genuinely try to connect it with your player's

380
00:18:53,263 --> 00:18:53,723
concerns.

381
00:18:54,644 --> 00:18:58,167
Show them that you know why they're frustrated, reiterate their concerns, and speak to their

382
00:18:58,187 --> 00:19:00,649
issues in a way that shows them that you're more than just a talking head.

383
00:19:02,718 --> 00:19:04,718
Anticipate how players will react to your comments.

384
00:19:05,219 --> 00:19:06,559
If you can anticipate their response,

385
00:19:06,819 --> 00:19:08,240
it makes it significantly easier

386
00:19:08,260 --> 00:19:09,540
to mitigate your expectations.

387
00:19:10,020 --> 00:19:11,281
If you write a response and think,

388
00:19:11,641 --> 00:19:13,061
this will probably make things worse,

389
00:19:13,481 --> 00:19:14,362
chances are it will.

390
00:19:14,902 --> 00:19:15,822
Show of hands real quick,

391
00:19:16,022 --> 00:19:17,523
who has written up a response in HitSend

392
00:19:17,543 --> 00:19:19,503
when they knew that it was gonna make the situation worse?

393
00:19:20,684 --> 00:19:21,124
Me too.

394
00:19:21,864 --> 00:19:22,544
It, don't do it.

395
00:19:23,504 --> 00:19:24,545
You're gonna keep doing it.

396
00:19:24,725 --> 00:19:25,585
I'm gonna keep doing it,

397
00:19:25,665 --> 00:19:26,885
but it never makes things easier.

398
00:19:27,246 --> 00:19:29,046
If you can recognize it before you HitSend,

399
00:19:29,666 --> 00:19:30,147
you have time.

400
00:19:32,553 --> 00:19:35,896
and bite your tongue, seriously.

401
00:19:36,857 --> 00:19:38,738
You may feel inclined to respond to the contrary

402
00:19:38,778 --> 00:19:40,440
and to prove the player wrong,

403
00:19:40,780 --> 00:19:43,042
but never allow yourself to respond while in this headspace.

404
00:19:43,602 --> 00:19:45,564
In some cases, honesty means telling a player

405
00:19:45,604 --> 00:19:46,365
that they're incorrect,

406
00:19:46,705 --> 00:19:48,326
but it never means that you should do so in a way

407
00:19:48,386 --> 00:19:50,468
that devalues their contribution to the community.

408
00:19:51,269 --> 00:19:53,150
As a side note, did you know that there's like

409
00:19:53,230 --> 00:19:55,953
a million photos of women biting laptops on Google?

410
00:19:59,796 --> 00:20:00,937
I hate it so much.

411
00:20:05,157 --> 00:20:07,378
So being honest and relatable gains you a lot of credit

412
00:20:07,418 --> 00:20:09,319
in the community and players are always thrilled

413
00:20:09,339 --> 00:20:11,419
that you took the time to talk to them on their level.

414
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:14,100
In one of the threads I mentioned earlier

